\begin{equation*}
\tilde{\nu} = \frac{1}{2 \pi c} \sqrt{\frac{k}{\mu}}
\end{equation*}

where:
- $\tilde{\nu}$ is the fundamental vibrational frequency in wavenumbers ($\mathrm{cm}^{-1}$)
- $c$ is the speed of light in vacuum ($2.998 \times 10^{10} \mathrm{cm} \cdot \mathrm{s}^{-1}$)
- $k$ is the force constant ($319 \mathrm{~N} \cdot \mathrm{m}^{-1}$)
- $\mu$ is the reduced mass of the molecule

First, let's calculate the reduced mass $\mu$:

\begin{equation*}
\mu = \frac{m_1 m_2}{m_1 + m_2}
\end{equation*}

For ${ }^{35} \mathrm{Cl}^{35} \mathrm{Cl}$, $m_1 = m_2 = 35$ amu. We need to convert the atomic mass unit (amu) to kilograms (kg) using the conversion factor $1 \mathrm{amu} = 1.66054 \times 10^{-27} \mathrm{kg}$. 

\begin{equation*}
m_1 = m_2 = 35 \times 1.66054 \times 10^{-27} \mathrm{kg} = 5.8119 \times 10^{-26} \mathrm{kg}
\end{equation*}

Now, calculate the reduced mass:

\begin{equation*}
\mu = \frac{(5.8119 \times 10^{-26} \mathrm{kg})^2}{2 \times 5.8119 \times 10^{-26} \mathrm{kg}} = 2.90595 \times 10^{-26} \mathrm{kg}
\end{equation*}

Next, convert the force constant from $\mathrm{N} \cdot \mathrm{m}^{-1}$ to $\mathrm{kg} \cdot \mathrm{s}^{-2}$:

\begin{equation*}
k = 319 \mathrm{~N} \cdot \mathrm{m}^{-1} = 319 \mathrm{~kg} \cdot \mathrm{s}^{-2}
\end{equation*}

Now, substitute the values into the formula for the fundamental vibrational frequency:

\begin{equation*}
\tilde{\nu} = \frac{1}{2 \pi (2.998 \times 10^{10} \mathrm{cm} \cdot \mathrm{s}^{-1})} \sqrt{\frac{319 \mathrm{~kg} \cdot \mathrm{s}^{-2}}{2.90595 \times 10^{-26} \mathrm{kg}}}
\end{equation*}

Simplify the expression inside the square root:

\begin{equation*}
\frac{319}{2.90595 \times 10^{-26}} = 1.0978 \times 10^{27} \mathrm{s}^{-2}
\end{equation*}

Take the square root:

\begin{equation*}
\sqrt{1.0978 \times 10^{27} \mathrm{s}^{-2}} = 1.048 \times 10^{13} \mathrm{s}^{-1}
\end{equation*}

