To find the percent ionization of a 0.20 M solution of methylamine, we can follow these steps:

Step 1: Write the ionization equation for methylamine.
\begin{align*}
\ce{CH3NH2 + H2O <=> CH3NH3+ + OH-}
\end{align*}

Step 2: Set up an ICE (Initial, Change, Equilibrium) table.
\begin{align*}
\begin{array}{c|ccc}
& \text{CH3NH2} & \text{CH3NH3+} & \text{OH-} \\
\hline
\text{Initial} & 0.20 & 0 & 0 \\
\text{Change} & -x & +x & +x \\
\text{Equilibrium} & 0.20-x & x & x
\end{array}
\end{align*}

Step 3: Write the Kb expression for methylamine.
\begin{align*}
Kb = \frac{[\text{CH3NH3+}][\text{OH-}]}{[\text{CH3NH2}]}
\end{align*}

Step 4: Calculate Kb from the given pKa value.
\begin{align*}
pKa + pKb = 14 \\
pKb = 14 - 10.64 = 3.36 \\
Kb = 10^{-3.36} = 4.4 \times 10^{-4}
\end{align*}

Step 5: Substitute the equilibrium concentrations into the Kb expression.
\begin{align*}
4.4 \times 10^{-4} = \frac{x^2}{0.20-x}
\end{align*}

Step 6: Assume x is small compared to 0.20 and simplify the equation.
\begin{align*}
4.4 \times 10^{-4} \approx \frac{x^2}{0.20} \\
x^2 = 4.4 \times 10^{-4} \times 0.20 = 8.8 \times 10^{-5} \\
x = \sqrt{8.8 \times 10^{-5}} = 9.4 \times 10^{-3}
\end{align*}

Step 7: Calculate the percent ionization.
\begin{align*}
\text{Percent ionization} = \frac{[\text{OH-}]}{[\text{CH3NH2}]_0} \times 100\% = \frac{9.4 \times 10^{-3}}{0.20} \times 100\% = 4.7\%
\end{align*}

Therefore, the percent ionization of a 0.20 M solution of methylamine is:
\begin{align*}
\boxed{4.7}\%
\end{align*}

